title: For Sale:  WWII .45acp Ammo.  Perfect Condition
postcontent:
Words off of the packing:  "50 Cartridges Pistol Ball Caliber .45 M1911 Ammunition Lot E.C. -24864xc Repacked E.C. 7-44"  
Ive done research and I have discovered that "E.C." stands for "Evansville Chrysler"  as in the Evansville Chrysler Plant that was used to produce war good during WWII.  The Ammo is headstamped "E" "C" "43".  The ammo and cardboard container are perfect condition, been dry since 1943.  Truly a piece of history, lead and brass were of very short supply... so the core and case are steel but the bullet is still copper FMJ.  The Ammunition is safe to fire, but I feel it is worth more as a piece of American History.  I have a few boxes, let me know if you are interested.  Asking $50 each.  Contact me at REDACTED -Tyler

title: For Sale:  Greco, Koster & Bark River fixed blades
postcontent:
First up is a John Greco fixed blade fighter called the Probos, though this one has a little extra jimping that Ive never seen before on another one. This one is also a little larger than most other I do believe. I bought this one off of John himself at the knife show in Cambridge OH several years back.

Anyways, it has John Grecos standard construction, 8670 steel, black coating, leather sheath by Sherry Lott, Micarta Scales.

Really really solid piece. It has seen some use and I have rebeveled the edge with my Edgepro. The coating has seen some wear in the middle of the blade and the rest of it, including sheath, has a scratch or bump here and there.

Would really make a great user for someone. Hell, kydex a sheath for this one (Something I never got around to) and it would make a hell of a tacticool blade you can actually use.

Overall I would rate the piece at 80% but has tons of life left in it.

I am asking $145 shipped USPS Priority with insurance to anywhere in the USA.

Pics

https://www.flickr.com/photos/104243672@N02/sets/REDACTED1192464/

Next is a Koster Survivor in A2 with a brown kydex sheath that has a large TekLock on it.

A2 steel. In really good condition but the blade does have some marks/discoloration on it (see the pics).

This has been used and the only reason Im selling it is Im moving away from large chopper and into the axe/small knife combos.

The balance and fit/finish on this knife are both really awesome. Dan puts out a really solid knife when you can get them.

Lets put this one at $325 shipped USPS priority with insurance anywhere in the USA.

Pics

https://www.flickr.com/photos/104243672@N02/sets/REDACTED1246254/

Last is a Bark River (BRKT) North Star EDC in CPM3V. Black canvas micarta scales. This one has only been used to break down 2-3 cardboard boxes but otherwise is mint. Has a few minor scratches/streaks on the blade but has not been sharpened or anything.

Lets but this one at $145 shipped USPS Priority with insurance anywhere in the USA.

This is a fine example of a RARE N Frame Smith & Wesson in .357 Magnum.

Smith & Wesson produced this revolver for the New York State Police in 1980. NYSP went a different direction, cancelled the order, and Smith sold the revolvers on the civilian market. Only 3000 were made. It has a 4 inch pinned barrel, a six shot recessed cylinder, a case hardened trigger and hammer, and fixed sights. To this day, the original 520 remains the ONLY fixed-sight N-Frame revolver Smith ever made in .357 Magnums. This would be perfect for your collection.

This is a beautiful gun that you just don't come across often. In this condition with box and papers, these guns sell well north of $1,250. Mine has no box and paper, and is priced accordingly.

REDACTED

There are also some non factory holes drilled in the left side of the receiver. I can only speculate that there was a "Peep Sight" mounted here at one time. The top of the receiver is drilled and tapped for scope mounting and there are screws present for mounting the bases. All of the mechanics worked fine during test firing. This is a great little rifle that can be shot with either the .357 mag. cal or 38 Spl. for economic shooting. Thanks for looking.
